{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:54:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:54:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16140"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16140"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.09,0.11,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8831"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74599"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8831"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16140"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60093"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9877"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21064"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74599"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPregnancy involves significant adaptations in osmoregulation to accommodate the needs of both mother and foetus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes changes in fluid regulation during normal pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased osmotic threshold for thirst and vasopressin release","Decreased vasopressin production","Increased osmotic threshold for thirst","Reduced placental vasopressinase activity","Unchanged vasopressin metabolism"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, there is a \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased osmotic threshold for thirst and vasopressin release\u003C/strong\u003E. This means that both thirst and vasopressin secretion are triggered at lower plasma osmolality than in non-pregnant individuals. This adaptation helps maintain the expanded plasma volume necessary during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased vasopressin production\u003C/strong\u003E - Vasopressin production increases to maintain fluid balance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased osmotic threshold for thirst\u003C/strong\u003E - The threshold is decreased, not increased\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced placental vasopressinase activity\u003C/strong\u003E - Placental vasopressinase activity is increased during pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnchanged vasopressin metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E - Vasopressin metabolism is significantly altered due to placental vasopressinase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes in fluid regulation are essential adaptations that help maintain appropriate fluid balance for both mother and developing foetus throughout pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["During pregnancy, vasopressin metabolism is altered due to increased placental vasopressinase activity.","The osmotic threshold for thirst and vasopressin release is reset lower during pregnancy to maintain expanded plasma volume.","These adaptations help maintain appropriate fluid balance for both mother and developing fetus."],"references":["Soma-Pillay P, Nelson-Piercy C, Tolppanen H, Mebazaa A. Physiological changes in pregnancy. Cardiovasc J Afr. 2016 Mar-Apr;27(2):89-94. doi: 10.5830/CVJA-2016-021. PMID: 27213856; PMCID: PMC4928162.","Song Y, Zhang F, Lin G, Wang X, He L, Li Y, Zhai Y, Zhang N, Ma G. A Study of the Fluid Intake, Hydration Status, and Health Effects among Pregnant Women in Their Second Trimester in China: A Cross-Sectional Study. Nutrients. 2023 Apr 2;15(7):1739. doi: 10.3390/nu15071739. PMID: 37049579; PMCID: PMC10096982.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60093"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16140"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60093"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T19:11:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T07:58:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8831"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74599"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"ht